ce:section.ce:para:
The CDs synthesis methods can be classified into two groups, including bottom-up approaches and top-down approaches (Fig. 2
                     ). For bottom-up approaches, CDs are synthesized by dehydrating and carbonizing small molecules such as carbohydrates, citric acid, etc. In addition, “bottom-up approaches” are commonly used in research because of their ability to synthesize large-scale, low-cost, and relatively simple control of the CDs properties. Top-down approaches require large-structure carbons, such as graphite, carbon nanotubes, and carbon rods, as carbon precursors. Chemical oxidation or physical processes, such as crushing or cutting, are then used to obtain ultra-small-sized carbon. The synthesis methods and their advantages and disadvantages are shown in Table 1
                     .
